Chuck E. Cheese: If you want a side of fun and games with your food, Chuck E. Cheese is offering a medium one-topping pizza and two drinks for $16.99 or two large one-topping pizzas with four drinks for $32.99. But the deals don’t stop on Pizza Day; visit chuckecheese.com/coupons-deals for coupons.
                                
                                    Chuck. E. Cheese

                                    Olive Garden

Blaze Pizza: Online special is two pepperoni pizzas for $10.
                                
                                    Blaze Fast Fire'd Pizza

                                    Domino's Pizza

Hungry Howie's: Order a large, two-topping pizza online (carryout only) for $7.99 using promo code LG799.
                                
                                    Hungry Howie's

Marco's: Get two medium one-topping pizzas for $6.99 or an XL Big Cheese for $9.99.
                                
                                    Marco’s Pizza

Papa Murphy's: Sign up at Papa Murphy's to get a coupon for 25 percent off in addition to access to other deals.
                                
                                    Papa Murphy's

Pizza Hut: Order two or more items for a select menu (items include things like medium one-topping pizza, boneless wings and stuffed garlic knots) for $5 each.

Caption: Hotel Valley Ho's Valentine's Day Show Stopper Shake (Photo11: Hotel Valley Ho)
People ride the Desert Storm roller coaster at Castles 'n' Coasters in Phoenix. (Photo11: David Wallace/The Republic)

FEB. 11 - COCKTAILS UNDER THE STARS AT MOUNTAIN SHADOWS: With its low light pollution, Mountain Shadows is the perfect spot for stargazing. On Monday, Feb. 11 from 6:30 to 8:30 p.m., the resort will host an astrology-themed cocktail reception on their rooftop deck — which overlooks Camelback Mountain. An astronomer will guide you to exploring the galaxy through the lens of a telescope. Tickets are $45 and include small bites along with two cocktails, glasses of wine or beer. You'll need to purchase your tickets at mountainshadows.com. 
                                
                                    Mountain Shadows

FEB. 13 - MUST LOVE DOGS: OMNI MONTELUCIA'S YAPPY HOUR: Maybe you and your Valentine love dogs. Maybe your dog is your Valentine. Either way, you can find cold noses and warm hearts at the Omni Montelucia's Yappy Hour at Crave Cafe on Feb. 13. For $15, you’ll receive a glass of wine during this Valentine’s Day-themed event. The date even comes with a charitable bonus: the resort says a portion of the proceeds benefit the #LovePup Foundation.
                                
                                    Mare Czinar/Special for The Republic

FEB. 13 - BUG LOVE AT BUTTERFLY WONDERLAND: Spend a night with your love bug — learning about bugs up close! On Feb. 13 from 6-8 p.m., Butterfly Wonderland is hosting an adults-only bug date night, which they hope will be educational and romantic. For $25 a couple, you can learn about the "love journeys" of bug amazing journeys of “love” and even sample some edible insect treats. Call 480-800-3000, ext. 210 for reservations.
                                
                                    The Republic

FEB. 14 - CASTLES AND COASTERS VALENTINE'S DAY SPECIAL: Family fun park Castles and Coasters is offering a Valentine's Day special. For $49.99, you can get a silver pass, which includes unlimited rides plus a round of golf for two plus two ice cream waffle cones. The deal is only available on Feb. 14. Just mention this deal to the cashier. 
                                
                                    David Wallace/The Republic

FEB. 14-16 - VERDE CANYON RAILROAD CHOCOLATE LOVER'S SPECIAL: Verde Canyon Railroad will host its popular Valentine's Day Chocolate Lover's Special in its first class cars Feb. 14, 15 and 16. Enjoy the spectacular views of the Arizona landscape paired with plated chocolates — as well as a Belgian Chocolate fountain with marshmallows, strawberries, pretzels and other fun things to dip. An upscale bar with wine and beer is also available. The trip costs $129 a person, and you can reserve a spot by calling 800-582-7245 or online.
                                    Verde Canyon Railroad

FEB. 14 -17 - BALLET ARIZONA'S THE FIREBIRD AND LA SYLPHIDE: Choreographer Ib Andersen's anticipated premiere of The Firebird — which the Ballet calls a "reimagined classical fairy tale, presented with a unique, mystifying and otherworldly twist" is paired with the romantic La Sylphide from Feb. 14-17. Tickets can be purchased through the ballet. 
                                
                                    Rosalie O'Connor

FEB. 15-16 - HOTEL VALLEY HO'S FEBRUARY SHOW STOPPER SHAKE: STRAWBERRY RED VELVET: Treat your sweet heart (or perhaps your little valentines) to the Strawberry Red Velvet Cream Cake “Show Stopper” Shake at the Hotel Valley Ho's ZuZu's restaurant. The shake is available during the restaurant's Valentine's day dinner as well as on Feb.15 and 16 from 11 a.m. to 11 p.m.  The jaw-dropping dessert features a white chocolate shake with strawberry gelato, strawberry red velvet cream cake, dark chocolate and strawberry ganache, marshmallow crème, capezzoli di venere truffles, and white-chocolate-covered strawberries. The showstopper shakes cost $16. 
                                
                                    Hotel Valley Ho

EVERY FRIDAY NIGHT - BILTMORE HAPPY HOUR HISTORY TOUR: If you’re looking for something affordable to do for a budding relationship, look no further than the Biltmore. Every Friday night at 6pm, the historic resort offers a history tour of their property lead by one of its resident historians. For $25, you get a quick walking tour of the some of the historic highlights of the resort along with two cocktails. It’s a great affordable (or perhaps first) date option — especially since if things are going well. You can stay for dinner at one of the resort’s restaurants and receive a 15% discount.
                                
                                    Melissa Yeager

Credit/Source: (Photo11: Courtesy of RISE Craft Coffee + Eatery)

Caption:
NITRO LIVE ICECREAMERY: As of mid-January, the Gilbert location of Nitro Live Icecreamery closed its doors at 884 W. Warner Road in Gilbert. A new location in Queen Creek will open in March. In the meantime, check the Nitro Live Ice Creamery Facebook page for information about pop-up events. 
                                
                                    Nitro Live Icecreamery

TAPHOUSE KITCHEN: 
North Phoenix is now home to a second location of TapHouse Kitchen. The contemporary, industrial restaurant serves a new menu created by Chef Patrick Karvis. Diners can enjoy dishes such as Shrimp Mac-n-Cheese, Chicken and Dumplings and Arizona-raised Prime New York Steak. DETAILS: 3131 E. Shea Blvd. 602-482-2800, taphousekitchen.com.
                                
                                    TapHouse Kitchen

TERIYAKI MADNESS: Dig into spicy chicken bowls, yakisoba and potstickers at Seattle-style teriyaki restaurant, Teriyaki Madness. Husband-and-wife duo Keith and Allison Colson opened the newest location of the fast-casual restaurant in Chandler last month. DETAILS: 4225 S. Gilbert Road #1, Chandler. 480-306-7807, teriyakimadness.com.
                                
                                    Courtesy of Teriyaki Madness

THAI CHILI 2 GO: The seventh Valley location of Thai Chili 2 Go opened in north Phoenix last month. The popular fast-casual restaurant got its start in the East Valley and serves dishes such as Thai Hot and Sour Soup, Pad Thai, Drunken Noodles and curries. DETAILS: 2750 W. Dove Valley Road, Phoenix. 480-566-8065, tc2go.com.
                                
                                    Courtesy of Joanie Simon

PDQ: PDQ — short for "People Dedicated to Quality" — opened its second Arizona location in Tempe. The restaurant specializes in chicken, which can be ordered in sandwiches, on bowls and fried and breaded along with one of the restaurant's eight sauces. DETAILS: 8905 S. Harl Ave., Tempe. 480-237-2313, eatpdq.com.
                                
                                    PDQ

CHICK-FIL-A: Now diners in the South Mountain neighborhood can enjoy chicken sandwiches and waffle fries from Chick-fil-A, which opened its newest metro Phoenix location in late January. Operator Stefan Bringas hired more than 100 staff for the new restaurant. DETAILS: 7650 S. 24th Street, Phoenix. 602-268-1257, chick-fil-a.com.
                                
                                    Chick-fil-a

KAZIMIERZ WINE AND WHISKEY BAR: Just a few months after the sudden closure of this well-loved Scottsdale bar and live music venue, a new owner has given the Kaz Bar a second life. Now a wine and whiskey bar, the spot serves food and live tunes from 4p.m. to 1 p.m. daily. DETAILS:  7137 E. Stetson Dr., Scottsdale. 480-946-3004, kazbarscottsdale.com.
                                
                                    Kazimierz Wine and Whiskey Bar

SCOOPWELL'S DOUGH BAR: Located at Uptown Plaza in central Phoenix. Scoopwell's Dough Bar serves made-from-scratch edible cookie dough in flavors including Brownie Batter, Rainbow Sprinkle and Lemon Poppyseed. Mix in toppings like of chocolate fudge, peanut butter chips, pretzels, Twix bars and more. DETAILS: 100 E. Camelback Road, #164, Phoenix. 602-296-5146, scoopwells.com.
                                
                                    Scoopwell's Dough Bar

MINGLE+GRAZE: 
Downtown Chandler is now home to a cheese shop and BYOB cafe called Mingle+Graze. Owner Mahfam Moeeni-Alarcon serves housemade soup, salads and sandwiches in the cozy space. DETAILS: 48 S. San Marcos Place, Chandler. facebook.com/mingleandgraze. 
                                
                                    Mingle+Graze

Caption:
Chengdu Delight | Chengdu Delight isn't quite the stuff of dreams for hard-core Sichuan traditionalists, but it's nice to have a spot that consistently scratches the itch. | Details: 2922 N. Alma School Road, Chandler. 480-963-1198, search for "Chengdu Delight" on Facebook.
                                
                                    Dominic Armato/ The Republic

Asian Hong Kong Diner|As Southern Chinese restaurants cede ground to other regional cuisines, restaurants like this are getting harder to come by. Asian Hong Kong Diner remains one of the best, where delicate Cantonese flavors are deftly woven into home-style dishes made with an unusual level of precision. |Details: 9880 S. Rural Road, Tempe. 480-705-7486.
                                
                                    Michael Schennum/The Republic

Great Wall Chinese Cuisine | This longtime stalwart of the Valley's Chinese scene still earns its stripes, and though it does a formidable job with the regular Cantonese menu, the big draw here is dim sum.|Details: 3446 W. Camelback Road, Phoenix. 602-973-1112, search for "Great Wall Cuisine" on Facebook.
                                
                                    Dominic Armato/The Republic

Mekong Palace |Big and boisterous, specialties include classic cart-served dim sum and an abundance of live seafood, prominently displayed in the dining room for you to select. |Details: Mekong Plaza, 66 S. Dobson Road, Mesa. 480-962-0493, search " Mekong Palace" on Facebook.
                                
                                    Patrick Breen/The Republic

Nan Zhou Hand Drawn Noodle House |
Nan Zhou's menu will be familiar to fans of the better-known China Magic Noodle House. The noodles at Nan Zhou trade the density of China Magic's for a playfully resilient elasticity. |Details: 111 S. Dobson Road, Mesa. 480-275-5352, nanzhounoodlemesa.com.
                                
                                    Dominic Armato/The Republic

Nee House | This is another Valley institution that still delivers, so long as you know where its strengths lie. Fried rice is unusually good, but the live seafood is always the star of the show, featuring whole crabs and lobsters chopped apart, stir-fried and sauced, and delivered on massive platters. | Details: 13843 N. Tatum Blvd., Phoenix. 602-992-3338, neehousephoenix.com.
                                
                                    Dominic Armato/The Republic

Chou's Kitchen | The godmother of the Valley's new wave of northern Chinese cuisine, Chou's Kitchen is still going strong as ever. | Details: 910 N. Alma School Road, Chandler. 480-821-2888.
                                
                                    Charlie Leight/The Republic

New Hong Kong Restaurant | New Hong Kong's neon marquee and Naugahyde booths have a dusty 1950s vibe, but the fare on the Chinese menu is a hearty, bold breed of Cantonese with some smart, non-canonical touches. | Details: 2328 E. Indian School Road, Phoenix. 602-954-9118, newhongkongphx.com.
                                
                                    Dominic Armato/The Republic

Phoenix Palace | Lighter and more welcoming in appearance than its West Valley counterpart, Phoenix Palace anchors the dim sum scene in the East Valley, serving up delicate dumplings, Cantonese classics and respectable barbecued meats to the weekend crowds. | Details: 2075 N. Dobson Road, Chandler. 480-855-4047, phoenixpalacechandleraz.com.
                                
                                    Tom Tingle/The Republic

Original Cuisine | Original Cuisine, the second location of a restaurant from Irvine, California, boasts a lengthy menu of dishes that tweak traditional Sichuan cuisine while maintaining its essential character, mixing up the fire and brimstone classics that Americans associate with the region and lesser-known dishes that cover a much broader spectrum of flavors. | Details: 1853 W. Broadway Road, Mesa. 480-255-7810, originalcuisineaz.com.
                                
                                    Tom Tingle/The Republic

Caption: Los Angeles Lakers guard Lonzo Ball would be a perfect fit on the Phoenix Suns, according to some NBA pundits. (Photo11: Kelvin Kuo-USA TODAY Sports)

The Suns have a history of wheeling and dealing. Here is a closer look at some notable trades in Suns history.
                                
                                    azcentral sports

Bledsoe to Milwaukee (2017) - The Suns shipped the disgruntled point guard to the Bucks in exchange for center Greg Monroe and a first and second round draft pick.
                                
                                    Benny Sieu-USA TODAY Sports

Tucker out (2017) - The trade: Toronto sent Jared Sullinger, along with its 2017 and 2018 second-round picks, to Phoenix for P.J. Tucker.
                                
                                    Michael Chow/azcentral sports

Goodbye, Markieff (2016) - The trade: the Suns sent Markieff Morris to the Wizards for a draft pick that would stay with the Wizards if it is in the draft's top nine. The Suns also acquired DeJuan Blair and Kris Humphries.
                                
                                    Jeff Swinger/USA TODAY Sports

Salary dump (2015) - The trade: The Suns sent Marcus Morris, Reggie Bullock and Danny Granger to create salary cap space in their pursuit of free agent LaMarcus Aldridge. The Suns received an unconditional 2020 second-round pick from the Pistons for sending out $8.4 million in salary for next season.
                                
                                    Rob Schumacher/azcentral sports

Wish granted (2015) - The trade: Prompted by a trade demand, Goran Dragic and his brother, Zoran, were traded to Miami for two first-round draft picks (2017, 2021), cash and Danny Granger.
                                
                                    Mark Henle/azcentral sports

Knight added (2015) - The trade: The Suns sent center Miles Plumlee and rookie point guard Tyler Ennis to Milwaukee, and the Lakers' first-round pick to Philadelphia. In return they landed combo guard Brandon Knight from the Bucks.
                                
                                    Benny Sieu-USA TODAY Sports

IT sent to Boston (2015) - The trade: Isaiah Thomas, on a four-year contract with decreasing salaries, was dealt to the Celtics for Cleveland's 2016 first-round pick and swingman Marcus Thornton, a volume scorer.
                                
                                    Mark J. Rebilas-USA TODAY Sports

Getting younger (2013) - The trade: Suns get Gerald Green and Miles Plumlee and a future first round pick from the Pacers for Luis Scola.
                                
                                    Cheryl Evans/azcentral sports

FEB. 11 - COCKTAILS UNDER THE STARS AT MOUNTAIN SHADOWS: With its low light pollution, Mountain Shadows is the perfect spot for stargazing. On Monday, Feb. 11 from 6:30 to 8:30 p.m., the resort will host an astrology-themed cocktail reception on their rooftop deck — which overlooks Camelback Mountain. An astronomer will guide you to exploring the galaxy through the lens of a telescope. Tickets are $45 and include small bites along with two cocktails, glasses of wine or beer. You'll need to purchase your tickets at mountainshadows.com. 
                                
                                    Mountain Shadows

FEB. 13 - MUST LOVE DOGS: OMNI MONTELUCIA'S YAPPY HOUR: Maybe you and your Valentine love dogs. Maybe your dog is your Valentine. Either way, you can find cold noses and warm hearts at the Omni Montelucia's Yappy Hour at Crave Cafe on Feb. 13. For $15, you’ll receive a glass of wine during this Valentine’s Day-themed event. The date even comes with a charitable bonus: the resort says a portion of the proceeds benefit the #LovePup Foundation.
                                
                                    Mare Czinar/Special for The Republic

FEB. 13 - BUG LOVE AT BUTTERFLY WONDERLAND: Spend a night with your love bug — learning about bugs up close! On Feb. 13 from 6-8 p.m., Butterfly Wonderland is hosting an adults-only bug date night, which they hope will be educational and romantic. For $25 a couple, you can learn about the "love journeys" of bug amazing journeys of “love” and even sample some edible insect treats. Call 480-800-3000, ext. 210 for reservations.
                                
                                    The Republic

FEB. 14 - CASTLES AND COASTERS VALENTINE'S DAY SPECIAL: Family fun park Castles and Coasters is offering a Valentine's Day special. For $49.99, you can get a silver pass, which includes unlimited rides plus a round of golf for two plus two ice cream waffle cones. The deal is only available on Feb. 14. Just mention this deal to the cashier. 
                                
                                    David Wallace/The Republic

FEB. 14-16 - VERDE CANYON RAILROAD CHOCOLATE LOVER'S SPECIAL: Verde Canyon Railroad will host its popular Valentine's Day Chocolate Lover's Special in its first class cars Feb. 14, 15 and 16. Enjoy the spectacular views of the Arizona landscape paired with plated chocolates — as well as a Belgian Chocolate fountain with marshmallows, strawberries, pretzels and other fun things to dip. An upscale bar with wine and beer is also available. The trip costs $129 a person, and you can reserve a spot by calling 800-582-7245 or online.
                                    Verde Canyon Railroad

FEB. 14 -17 - BALLET ARIZONA'S THE FIREBIRD AND LA SYLPHIDE: Choreographer Ib Andersen's anticipated premiere of The Firebird — which the Ballet calls a "reimagined classical fairy tale, presented with a unique, mystifying and otherworldly twist" is paired with the romantic La Sylphide from Feb. 14-17. Tickets can be purchased through the ballet. 
                                
                                    Rosalie O'Connor

FEB. 15-16 - HOTEL VALLEY HO'S FEBRUARY SHOW STOPPER SHAKE: STRAWBERRY RED VELVET: Treat your sweet heart (or perhaps your little valentines) to the Strawberry Red Velvet Cream Cake “Show Stopper” Shake at the Hotel Valley Ho's ZuZu's restaurant. The shake is available during the restaurant's Valentine's day dinner as well as on Feb.15 and 16 from 11 a.m. to 11 p.m.  The jaw-dropping dessert features a white chocolate shake with strawberry gelato, strawberry red velvet cream cake, dark chocolate and strawberry ganache, marshmallow crème, capezzoli di venere truffles, and white-chocolate-covered strawberries. The showstopper shakes cost $16. 
                                
                                    Hotel Valley Ho

Efrain Javier Gonzalez, 31, in Nogales, Mexico. Gonzalez from Guerrero, fled from violence and extortion. He is with family, plan on asking for asylum at the Nogales port of entry if that does not happen they will try to cross with the help of human smugglers. President Trump is directing asylum seekers to go to the ports, but the metering policy at the ports drives some asylum seekers to cross illegally with the help of smugglers because the waits are so long. (Photo11: Nick Oza/The Republic)

Date: Published 7:42 p.m. MT Feb. 1, 2019
Caption: Bombay Beach at the Salton Sea in California was once a playground for the elite, but now the crusty, salty beach is a reminder of the ecological trade-offs of growing urban water demands. The Southwest’s worsening water shortage will make saving the Salton Sea difficult, because any fix would require water from an over-stressed Colorado River. (Photo11: Mark Henle/The Republic)

A boat goes by silt banks towering over 50-feet above the Colorado River near Pearce Ferry, making the end of the Grand Canyon, in Lake Mead National Recreation Area. The massive silt banks come from silt that came down the Colorado River and could not pass Hoover Dam. These silt banks were once underwater in Lake Mead but with the lake at near record low levels, the silt banks line the river. (Photo11: David Wallace/The Republic)
Gov. Doug Ducey (right) signs the Drought Contingency Plan on Jan. 31, 2019, in the historic Senate Chamber, at the Arizona state Capitol. (Photo11: Mark Henle/The Republic)

The Cochinita Pibil (pulled pork) at Barrio Cafe. (Photo11: The Republic)

In an episode of “Guy’s Family Road Trip,” celebrity chef Guy Fieri explored northern Arizona and its cuisine. "Definitely in the top 20 most crazy places I've ever been to," Fieri said. (Photo11: Dominic Armato/The Republic)

Giuseppe's on 28th | Guy Fieri visited Giuseppe's on 28th for his Food Network show "Diners, Drive-Ins and Dives." He said the Bolognese ragu was "crazy good." | Details: 2824 E. Indian School Road, Phoenix. 602-381-1237, giuseppeson28th.com. (Photo11: Courtesy of Giuseppe's on 28th)
A Belgian waffle is topped with smoked ribs at Joe's Farm Grill in Gilbert. (Photo11: Joanie Simon)

La Santisima Gourmet Taco Shop | “Triple D" and Guy Fieri featured some of this taqueria’s most popular items during a 2015 visit. Fieri tried the carne asada taco and the Baja Sur dogfish shark taco, beer-battered dogfish shark fried and stuffed into a corn tortilla.
Details: 1919 N. 16th St., Phoenix. 602-254-6330, lasantisimagourmet.com. (Photo11: John Samora/The Republic)

Paradise Valley Burger Company: The restaurant, which was featured on Food Network’s “Diners, Drive-Ins and Dives,” will serve such specialties as the Beach House Burger, topped with roasted green chile, smoked mozzarella and pico de gallo. It’s located along the main concourse near Section 121. (Photo11: Jennifer Stewart/Arizona Diamondbacks)

Tacos Chiwas | Guy Fieri stopped at Tacos Chiwas in 2017, an acclaimed taco joint on McDowell Road near 20th Street. | Details: 1923 E. McDowell Road, Phoenix. 602-358-8830, tacoschiwas.com. (Photo11: Dominic Armato/The Republic)

A meal from Suh Noi - The Little Thaiger. Suh Noi is the little sister to the popular Wild Thaiger restaurant Guy Fieri visited for his show "Diners, Drive-Ins and Dives" back in December. (Photo11: The Little Thaiger)

FEB. 2-3 - ARIZONA VEGETARIAN FOOD FESTIVAL: Back for its fifth year, the Arizona Vegetarian Food Festival takes over Scottsdale Civic Center Plaza for two days of food and fun. In addition to featuring 60 vegan vendors, the event includes presentations, yoga, workout classes, kids' activities, and music. DETAILS: 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Saturday, Feb. 2-Sunday, Feb. 3. Scottsdale Civic Center Mall, 3939 N. Drinkwater Blvd., Scottsdale. $20. azvegfoodfest.com.
                                
                                    The Republic

FEB. 9 - ARIZONA STRONG BEER FESTIVAL: Arizona Beer Week includes hundreds of events all over the state, but the don't-miss action will be at the Arizona Strong Beer Festival. More than 150 breweries from around the state and country will gather in central Phoenix to tap and taste specialty, unique and rare brews. Admission includes 40 tasting tickets with VIP tickets available for those interested in perks like early entry and private restrooms. DETAILS: 1-5 p.m. Saturday, Feb 9. Steele Indian School Park, 300 E. Indian School Road, Phoenix. $60. 480-365-9000, arizonabeerweek.com/arizona-strong-beer-festival.
                                
                                    Melissa Fossum/azcentral.com

FEB. 16 - THE CHILI BOURBON FESTIVAL: Local home cooks and chefs can compete in this downtown Chandler cook-off. A ticket includes a tasting card to sample from the competitors and the right to vote for your favorite. The event also will feature more than a dozen types of bourbon, which will be available to sample with the purchase of a drink card. DETAILS: Noon-9 p.m. Saturday, Feb. 16. Dr. AJ Chandler Park, 178 E. Commonwealth Ave., Chandler. $10. chilibourbonfestival.com.
                                
                                    Chili Bourbon Festival

FEB. 16 - LAVEEN BBQ FESTIVAL: Hosted by the not-for-profit Laveen Community Council, this 6th annual event includes barbecue, cold drinks, family-friendly games, and live entertainment. DETAILS: 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Saturday, Feb. 16. Cesar Chavez Park, 7858 S. 35th Ave., Laveen. $10. Laveenbbq.org.
                                
                                    Laveen BBQ Festival

FEB. 16 - SCOTTSDALE TACO CRAWL: Inhale tacos and exhale negativity at this bar crawl with a hefty side of tacos. Taco and tequila lovers will sample tacos at several Old Town Scottsdale bars, which include Casa Amigos, Goodwood Tavern, Old Town Gringos, Skylanes, El Chameleon, and Wasted Grain. Tickets include six tacos and drink specials at each location. DETAILS: noon-6 p.m. Saturday, Feb. 16. Multiple locations. $20. scottsdaletacocrawl.weebly.com.
                                
                                    Arizona Taco Festival

FEB. 16-17 - STREET EATS FOOD TRUCK FESTIVAL: Fifty-five food trucks will roll into Salt River Fields in Scottsdale for this two-day fest. Every truck will serve a $2 sample menu so attendees can taste as much street food as possible. Food is not included in the general-admission ticket price. Entertainment will include live bands, lawn games, eating contests, local vendors, cooking classes and more. DETAILS: 11 a.m.-6 p.m. Saturday, Feb. 16 and Sunday, Feb. 17. Salt River Fields at Talking Stick, 7555 N.  Pima Road, Scottsdale. $12. streeteatsaz.com.
                                
                                    Street Eats Food Truck Festival

FEB. 16-17 - THE COCKTAIL JAM: Kick off Arizona Cocktail Week at this music and mixology party at the Van Buren in downtown Phoenix. DJ Z-Trip will perform and admission includes 10 cocktail samples. DETAILS: 8 p.m. Saturday, Feb. 16, to 2 a.m. Sunday, Feb 17. The Van Buren, 12 W. Camelback Road, Phoenix. $50. Arizonacocktailweekend.com.
                                
                                    Arizona Cocktail Weekend

Tucker out (2017) - The trade: Toronto sent Jared Sullinger, along with its 2017 and 2018 second-round picks, to Phoenix for P.J. Tucker.
                                
                                    Michael Chow/azcentral sports

Goodbye, Markieff (2016) - The trade: the Suns sent Markieff Morris to the Wizards for a draft pick that would stay with the Wizards if it is in the draft's top nine. The Suns also acquired DeJuan Blair and Kris Humphries.
                                
                                    Jeff Swinger/USA TODAY Sports

Salary dump (2015) - The trade: The Suns sent Marcus Morris, Reggie Bullock and Danny Granger to create salary cap space in their pursuit of free agent LaMarcus Aldridge. The Suns received an unconditional 2020 second-round pick from the Pistons for sending out $8.4 million in salary for next season.
                                
                                    Rob Schumacher/azcentral sports

Wish granted (2015) - The trade: Prompted by a trade demand, Goran Dragic and his brother, Zoran, were traded to Miami for two first-round draft picks (2017, 2021), cash and Danny Granger.
                                
                                    Mark Henle/azcentral sports

Knight added (2015) - The trade: The Suns sent center Miles Plumlee and rookie point guard Tyler Ennis to Milwaukee, and the Lakers' first-round pick to Philadelphia. In return they landed combo guard Brandon Knight from the Bucks.
                                
                                    Benny Sieu-USA TODAY Sports

IT sent to Boston (2015) - The trade: Isaiah Thomas, on a four-year contract with decreasing salaries, was dealt to the Celtics for Cleveland's 2016 first-round pick and swingman Marcus Thornton, a volume scorer.
                                
                                    Mark J. Rebilas-USA TODAY Sports

Getting younger (2013) - The trade: Suns get Gerald Green and Miles Plumlee and a future first round pick from the Pacers for Luis Scola.
                                
                                    Cheryl Evans/azcentral sports

Caption: Sedona is grappling with a state law that has prohibited cities and towns from regulating home rentals took effect. Before the new law took effect, there were an estimated 200-300 homes available in Sedona as vacation rentals. Today, rentals have grown to more than 1,000, or 20 percent of Sedona’s total housing. (Photo11: Lorraine Longhi/Special for The Republic)

El Portal is just one establishment in Sedona that has been impacted by the rise in short-term rentals that has created competition for boutique hotels and bed and breakfasts that have long been a staple of the tourist town. (Photo11: Lorraine Longhi/The Republic)

Sedona City Councilmember Scott Jablow stands in front of a home being operated as a short-term rental. City officials and residents say the law has exacerbated a growing problem of unavailable housing that could have far-reaching consequences for their city. (Photo11: Lorraine Longhi/The Republic)
Sedona closed one of its two elementary schools last year after a slow decline in enrollment over the last decade. (Photo11: Lorraine Longhi/The Republic)
